Hello,

Up until version 3.0.0 `fetch-retry` came bundled with `isomorphic-fetch` and used that to wrap "fetch". In later versions, this is no longer the case, and you have to install a fetch library yourself, and then wrap that with `fetch-retry` (see the code example below). 

The advantage of this approach is that you get to decide which package to use, and most likely you already have a packed installed, so installing fetch-retry will not have a big impact on your overall bundle size. In addition, this also means that `fetch-retry` doesn't need any production dependencies itself which is a great bonus. The downside is that it's a little bit more hassle to  setup `fetch-retry` initially in your project.

```
var originalFetch = require('isomorphic-fetch');
var fetch = require('fetch-retry')(originalFetch);

fetch(url, {
    retries: 3,
    retryDelay: 1000
  })
  .then(function(response) {
    return response.json();
  })
  .then(function(json) {
    // do something with the result
    console.log(json);
  });
```

